#4: The missing relationship in the diagram is that each weather observation is linked to a specific airport. This relationship exists through the origin field in the weather table, which corresponds to the faa field in the airports table. To represent this in the diagram, an arrow should be drawn from weather.origin to airports.faa. This indicates that each weather record belongs to a specific airport, establishing a foreign key relationship between the two tables.

#5:

names <- c("year", "month", "day", "hour", "origin")
weather$weather_id <- ""
for (var in names) {
  weather$weather_id <- paste0(weather$weather_id,
                           ifelse(weather$weather_id == "", "", "-"),
                           weather[[var]])
}

num_dupes <- sum(duplicated(weather$weather_id))
cat("Number of duplicated weather_id values:", num_dupes, "\n")
Number of duplicated weather_id values: 3 
unique(weather$weather_id[duplicated(weather$weather_id)])
[1] "2013-11-3-1-EWR" "2013-11-3-1-JFK" "2013-11-3-1-LGA"

After creating a new variable weather_id by combining year, month, day, hour, and origin, I found 3 duplicated weather_id values (2013-11-3-1 at EWR, JFK, and LGA). These duplicates exist because daylight saving time ended on November 3, 2013, causing the 1 AM hour to occur twice. Since we used only year, month, day, hour, and origin, these two distinct 1 AM observations appear as duplicates.

6: check expectations:

Higher precip â longer delays. Lower visib â longer delays. Stronger wind_gust â longer delays. temp may not have a direct effect.

7: validate with an external source Using NOAA 2013 NYC weather reports, we know: Major snowstorms occurred in February and March. Thunderstorms were frequent in JulyâAugust.These periods correspond to higher average flight delays â validating that weather events truly affect flight operations.

flights_weather <- flights_weather %>%
  mutate(
    temp_cat = case_when(
      temp < 40 ~ "Cold (<40Â°F)",
      temp < 70 ~ "Mild (40â70Â°F)",
      TRUE      ~ "Warm (>70Â°F)"
    ),
    wind_cat = case_when(
      wind_speed < 10 ~ "Calm (<10 mph)",
      wind_speed < 20 ~ "Moderate (10â20 mph)",
      TRUE            ~ "Windy (>20 mph)"
    ),
    visib_cat = case_when(
      visib < 2 ~ "Low (<2 mi)",
      visib < 5 ~ "Moderate (2â5 mi)",
      TRUE      ~ "High (>5 mi)"
    ),

Delay vs Precipitation

flights_weather <- flights_weather %>%
  mutate(
    precip_cat = case_when(
      precip == 0 ~ "None",
      precip > 0 & precip <= 0.5 ~ "Light",
      precip > 0.5 & precip <= 1.0 ~ "Moderate",
      precip > 1.0 ~ "Heavy",
      TRUE ~ "Unknown"
    )
  )

flights_weather %>%
  group_by(precip_cat) %>%
  summarise(avg_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = precip_cat, y = avg_delay, fill = precip_cat)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    title = "Average Departure Delay by Precipitation Level",
    x = "Precipitation Category",
    y = "Average Delay (min)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Weather phenomena that most impact flight delays are precipitation and low visibility, with heavy rain/snow days showing the largest average departure delays. Wind also contributes but to a lesser extent, while temperature alone is not a major driver.
